@ptn・8 We want to propose a fairly substantial change to how PTN operates, and look forward to your feedback as we finalize specifics. We introduced our checkpoint system three months ago, with the intention of tracking real time losses and risk assumed by the miners. Since then, it has become the core of the scoring mechanic on PTN. These checkpoints allow us to track real time performance of miners, giving us key insight into real time risk adjusted returns. We have built a number of scoring and consistency metrics on top of this checkpoints structure, which are meant to discourage unsustainable trading behavior and moderate reasonable behavior for our challenge period.

The checkpoints system is also confusing. We need to simplify our system, better communicate the quality of our traders to clients, and encourage miners to close positions so we have more touch points on their strategies. **To accomplish this, we will move away from checkpoints for evaluating miner return, instead opting to use returns from closed positions.** To avoid the scenario where miners never close losing positions, their realized returns will include:

- Positions opened and closed within the look back window
- Any open positions in loss

In building out the checkpoints, we developed a number of great tools to evaluate miner performance, primarily our risk normalization using real time drawdown. We will continue to use open positions for risk evaluation, consistent with how we were measuring drawdown before. We will additionally rely on the checkpoints to penalize inconsistent growth - if a majority of a miner’s portfolio value increase comes from a single day, they will be penalized.

We will also update the challenge period to incorporate positional returns, removing sortino and volume based checkpoints entirely. Here are the new proposed criteria for challenge period, consistent with the new position based scoring system:

- [Realized Return] 2% return from closed positions and open positions in loss
- [Realized Return] Max return from single closed position no larger than 25% of total returns
- [Unrealized Return] A single day of trading should not represent more than 20% of the total returns
- [Unrealized Return] Max drawdown of less than 5%

Miners currently in challenge period may request a clean slate. We will wipe positions / checkpoints and restart your challenge period. We will also roll out these changes with an increase to the look back window from 30 days to 90 days. Details on this increased look back window will be provided tomorrow with another update and proposal, as well as more information regarding the overall timeline of introduction.

Anytime you can get a ticket to play this game below $17.50 with these odds you get +EV.

Now lets say in this game there are skilled players with well callibrated models and non-skilled players:
3 out of 10 are skilled and have a 20% chance of winning, while the other 7 participants share the remaining equally. 
FV (skilled) is now $35

As you decrease the cost of entry your expected value to play increase no matter your edge. Hi @kabar , the positional return criteria means that a single position can't account for more than 25% of the total return. If I have 5 equally sized closed positions with a return of 0.4%, then my total return will be 2% and the max ratio will be 0.4% / 2% = 0.2 = 20%. This is below the threshold of 25%, so this passes. This ratio will always be computed against the current total positional return, so as you close more winning positions the ratio will decrease for your older positions.

The single day earning of 20% looks at a sliding window of portfolio value change (unrealized gains), and compares this to your total unrealized gain over the period. If your final portfolio value is 4% in challenge period, then we check that no more than 1% of this growth was from a single 24 hour window (window could be from 6AM to 6AM, or 12AM to 12AM, doesn't start at midnight every day). If your total final unrealized portfolio value increases to 5%, then we check that no more than 1.25% of your value gain comes from a single 24 hour window. This structure is meant to help protect from the scenario where a miner makes a number of bets against the same asset class (for example, EURUSD, CADUSD, GBPUSD), spreading a single market movement over multiple positions.

To clear things up, yes, the unrealized ratio threshold ensures that "one day shouldn't be more than 20% of the total returns" (although this will be relaxed a bit in a few days). 
A miner with a realized profit of 1.1% can still have a high unrealized ratio since this would be:
A = the maximum of gains + losses for a day
B = the total sum of gains + losses over the whole challenge period
Unrealized ratio = A/B 

The realized return isn't considered in this calculation. These (gains + losses) are determined by open positions at each checkpoint rather than returns at closed positions like the other challenge period thresholds. This allows us to consider the risk of open positions on strategies. Check out this code for more details: https://github.com/taoshidev/proprietary-trading-network/blob/574f77065cdbb8709d1ccf7c9411d439fd0f5cf0/vali_objects/utils/ledger_utils.py#L257

@ptn・8 We are releasing the PR for proposal 14. In it you will find clarification on daily returns element for long term and short term, as well as a slight modification to the penalties through the removal of the returns ratio and introduction of the Herfindahl–Hirschman Index (HHI). Hopefully this brings our system one step closer to traditional intuitions in finance. P14 has been updated accordingly:  You will also find minimum thresholds for the number of days before confidence in measuring a few of our metrics: sharpe ratio, sortino, omega, and tstat. The current scoring weights for each category may be subject to slight tuning, but we anticipate they will look like this:

SCORING_LONG_RETURN_LOOKBACK_WEIGHT = 0.2
SCORING_SHORT_RETURN_LOOKBACK_WEIGHT = 0.1
SCORING_SHARPE_WEIGHT = 0.175
SCORING_OMEGA_WEIGHT = 0.175
SCORING_SORTINO_WEIGHT = 0.175
SCORING_STATISTICAL_CONFIDENCE_WEIGHT = 0.175

The HHI penalty (https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Herfindahl%E2%80%93Hirschman_index) measures concentration, and is meant to penalize high concentration of returns in a manner quite similar to the returns ratio. Typical concentration values on this index range between 0 and 10,000. Low concentrations (high levels of diversity) typically have scores in the range of 0 - 1,500, medium concentrations between 1,500 and 2,500, and high concentrations in excess of 2,500. Concentrations are high when the behavior of the system is generally dominated by just a few days or positions.

While our target release is still Dec 3, this is subject to change depending on the state of the challenge period release and internal robustness testing for the changes. Looking forward to your feedback.

After seeing the score weights, I believe some points are worth discussing. For example, traders might need to stop earning more this day to keep returns lower, as higher returns could reduce the weight.

While low volatility is good, overemphasizing it could favor grid trading or Martingale-like strategies, which perform well in normal conditions but fail under extreme risks. Assuming that daily alpha (excess returns) remains constant is unrealistic.

**Excess returns shouldn’t be penalized, as this contradicts the purpose of trading: earn more money.** A better approach in my opinion would be to reduce their weight, treating them like outliers in statistics rather than oversimplifying with restrictive indicators. These indicators are generally designed to help traders quickly filter through a large number of potential targets, not to serve as direct constraints on their strategies.

So I believe we need more creative approaches, allowing real-world trading strategies to run directly on this subnet, thereby increasing the subnet's competitiveness.

Very nice proposal. @Derek | Taoshi [τ, θ] Just to clarify on the Martingale penalty algorithm - from the docs *"For each position, we will count the position as a potential martingale if it increases the maximum leverage on a losing position at least twice."*.  
Lets assume losing position contains one order with leverage 1. Here are my questions:

a) if another order with leverage 1 is added to the position (new total leverage is 2), does it "*increase leverage twice*"?, or new order with leverage 2 needs to be added, so that new total leverage on the position is 3?

b) if I add additional 4 orders to this position (lets assume 24hrs break between each new order), every order with leverage 0.5, will that qualify for martingale penalty?

c) if I put opposite direction order to reduce the leverage on this losing position by half, and then after some time I add few additional orders so that:
        c1) reduced leverage is *increased twice*
        c2) original leverage is *increased twice*
    will that count towards Martingale penalty?

Great questions @kabar. 

a) This would not increase the leverage twice. This would be one martingale step and would not be flagged. However, any increase from the max leverage is counted. With an order of 1 leverage and another order of 1 leverage (now a cumulative leverage of 2), any order that increases it from 2 would be counted as a martingale step provided it is still a losing position. 

b) Yes, these would be possible martingale steps if the position is losing when the orders are placed. 

c) The proposed system considers max leverage on the position. 
        c1) A reduced leverage that increases doesn't count as a martingale step unless it surpasses the max leverage already seen.
        c2) If it is a losing position when the order is placed, a change in leverage will only be counted as a martingale step if it increases the magnitude of the leverage beyond the maximum already seen.

To summarize, the entry/first order sets the initial baseline for a position. After this, any orders that increase the leverage beyond the maximum leverage seen (magnitude is used to account for positions with positive or negative leverage) will be martingale steps given that the position is losing. 2 or more martingale steps on any position will then increase your martingale penalty.
